<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<worksheet>
  <title>GR-2 Polynomial Functions</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      This outcome covers polynomial functions. You should be able to identify the degree and leading 
      coefficient of a polynomial function. Be able to determine the end behavior of a polynomial 
      function. You should also be able to find the x-intercepts and y-intercept of a polynomial function.  
      You should also be able to graph polynomial functions.  You should be able to write out complete 
      steps to solve these types of problems by hand, without the use of a calculator.
    </p>
    <p>For the quiz on this outcome you would be given 30 minutes to complete 2 problems. Here are samples 
      of the types of problems you will encounter:</p>
  </introduction>
  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Simplifying Expressions: Simplify algebraic expressions by combining like terms and applying the 
        distributive property. Answers should be completely simplified.</p></li>
        <li><p>Basics of Graphing: Give a graph with appropriate scales and labels. The line should have the 
          correct intercepts and general behavior.</p></li>
      <li><p>Problem structure: Solution should be organized and easy to follow, with clear, complete steps 
        that follow progressively from one to the next.</p></li>
      <li><p>Mathematical Communication: Solutions should be presented in a clear and logical manner, with 
        appropriate use of mathematical notation and terminology. Equations should have at most one equal 
        sign and expressions on both sides.</p></li>
      <li><p>End Behavior: Determine the end behavior of a polynomial function and write this using 
        correct notation.</p></li>
      <li><p>Write in Factored Form: Use the Possible Rational Root Theorem and division to write a polynomial 
        function in factored form.</p></li>
      <li><p>Intercepts and Zeros: Find the zeros and multiplicities and the y-intercept of a polynomial function.</p></li>
      <li><p>Graphing: Graph the function with appropriate scales and labels, showing the correct 
        intercepts and general behavior.</p></li>
    </ul>
    </objectives>

  
  <page>
    <exercise workspace="3cm">
      <introduction><p>
           Given the function <m>f(x)=-3(x-1)^3(x+2)(x+1)^2</m>.
      </p></introduction>
      <task>
        <statement><p>State the degree and leading coefficient of <m>f(x)</m>.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>Look at the exponents of each factor to find the degree. Look at the coefficient 
          of the highest degree term to find the leading coefficient.</p></hint>
        <answer><p>Degree: 6, Leading Coefficient: -3</p></answer>
        <solution><p>To find the degree of the polynomial, we add up the exponents 
          of the factors. The degree is 3 + 1 + 2 = 6.</p></solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><p>State the end behavior of <m>f(x)</m>, using correct notation.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>Since the degree is even and the leading coefficient is negative, the end behavior will be 
          the same on both sides and will go down.</p></hint>
        <answer><p>As <m>x \to \infty</m>, <m>f(x) \to -\infty</m>. As <m>x \to -\infty</m>, <m>f(x) \to -\infty</m>.</p></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><p>State the x-intercepts and y-intercept of <m>f(x)</m>.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>To find the x-intercepts, set each factor equal to zero and solve for x. To find the y-intercept, 
          evaluate the function at x=0.</p></hint>
        <answer><p>x-intercepts: (1,0), (-2,0), (-1,0); y-intercept: (0, -6)</p></answer>
        <solution><p>To find the x-intercepts, we set each factor equal to zero and solve for x. 
          Setting <m>(x-1)^3=0</m> gives us the x-intercept (1,0). Setting <m>(x+2)=0</m> gives us the x-intercept 
          (-2,0). Setting <m>(x+1)^2=0</m> gives us the x-intercept (-1,0).</p></solution>
      </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise workspace="3cm">
      <introduction><p>
           Given the function <m>g(x)=2x^4+8x^3+4x^2-8x-6</m>.
      </p></introduction>
          <task>
            <statement><p>State the degree and leading coefficient of <m>g(x)</m>.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>Look at the highest degree term to find the degree and leading coefficient.</p></hint>
            <answer><p>Degree: 4, Leading Coefficient: 2</p></answer>
            <solution><p>To find the degree of the polynomial, we look at the highest degree term, 
              which is <m>2x^4</m>. The degree is 4 and the leading coefficient is 2.</p></solution>
          </task>
          <task>  
            <statement><p>State the end behavior of <m>g(x)</m>, using correct notation.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>Since the degree is even and the leading coefficient is positive, the end behavior will be 
              the same on both sides and will go up.</p></hint>
            <answer><p>As <m>x \to \infty</m>, <m>g(x) \to \infty</m>. As <m>x \to -\infty</m>, 
              <m>g(x) \to \infty</m>.</p></answer>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement><p>State the x-intercepts and y-intercept of <m>g(x)</m>.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>To find the x-intercepts, set the function equal to zero and solve for x. To find the y-intercept, 
              evaluate the function at x=0.</p></hint>
            <answer><p>x-intercepts: (1,0), (-1,0), (-3,0); y-intercept: (0, -6)</p></answer>
            <solution><p>To find the x-intercepts, we set the function equal to zero and solve for x.We can use the 
              Rational Root Theorem to find possible rational roots, which are factors of the constant term (-6) 
              divided by factors of the leading coefficient (2). Then use synthetic division to test these possible 
              roots until we find one that works (gives a remainder of zero).
              Setting <m>2x^4+8x^3+4x^2-8x-6=0</m> gives us the x-intercepts (1,0), (-1,0), and (-3,0). 
              To find the y-intercept, we evaluate the function at x=0: <m>g(0)=2(0)^4+8(0)^3+4(0)^2-8(0)-6=-6</m>. 
              Therefore, the y-intercept is (0, -6).</p></solution>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement><p>Sketch the graph of <m>g(x)</m>, showing the correct intercepts and general behavior.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>Use the end behavior, intercepts, behavior at the roots and general shape of the graph to sketch it.</p></hint>
            <answer>
              <image width="60%">
              <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                          label="prefigure-gr2a-sample">
                <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                  <definition>g(x)=2*x^4+8*x^3+4*x^2-8*x-6</definition>
                  <coordinates bbox="(-5,-10,5,15)">
                    <grid spacings="((-5,1,5),(-10,5,15))"/>
                    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                    <graph function="g"/>
                    <point p="(0,-6)" alignment="s">y-intercept</point>
                    <point p="(-1,0)" alignment="n">x-intercept</point>
                    <point p="(-3,0)" alignment="nw">x-intercept</point>
                    <point p="(1,0)" alignment="ne">x-intercept</point>
                  </coordinates>
                  <annotations>
                    <annotation ref="figure"
                                text="The graph is a quartic function (with a W-shape) opening 
                                upwards with y-intercept at (0, -6), and x-intercepts at 
                                (-3, 0), (-1, 0), and (1, 0).">
                      </annotation>
                  </annotations>
                </diagram>
              </prefigure>
            </image>
          </answer>
          </task>
        </exercise>
    <exercise workspace="3cm">
      <introduction><p>
        Given the function <m>p(x)=-x^4-2x^3+3x^2+4x-4</m>.
      </p></introduction>
        <task>
          <statement><p>State the end behavior of <m>p(x)</m>, using correct notation.</p></statement>
          <hint><p>Since the degree is even and the leading coefficient is negative, the end behavior will be 
            the same on both sides and will go down.</p></hint>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement><p>Write <m>p(x)</m> in factored form.</p></statement>
          <hint><p>Use the Possible Rational Root Theorem to find a root, then use synthetic division to factor the polynomial. 
            Repeat this process until the polynomial is completely factored.</p></hint>
          <answer><p><m>p(x)=-1(x-1)(x+2)(x^2+x-2)</m></p></answer>
          <solution><p>To factor the polynomial, we first use the Possible Rational Root Theorem to find a root. 
            We test the factors of the constant term (-4) and the leading coefficient (-1). We find that x=1 is a 
            root. We then use synthetic division to divide the polynomial by (x-1). This gives us a quotient of 
            <m>-1(x^3+x^2-2x-4)</m>. We then factor the quotient using synthetic division again, finding that x=-2 
            is a root. This gives us a quotient of <m>-1(x^2+x-2)</m>. We can then factor this further to get 
            <m>p(x)=-1(x-1)(x+2)(x-1)(x+2)</m>.</p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement><p>Sketch the graph of <m>p(x)</m>, showing the correct intercepts 
            and general behavior.</p></statement>
          <hint><p>Use the end behavior, intercepts, behavior at the roots and general shape of the graph to sketch it.</p></hint>
          <answer>
              <image width="60%">
              <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                          label="prefigure-gr2b-sample">
                <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                  <definition>p(x)=-x^4-2*x^3+3*x^2+4*x-4</definition>
                  <coordinates bbox="(-5,-20,5,5)">
                    <grid spacings="((-5,1,5),(-20,5,5))"/>
                    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                    <graph function="p"/>
                    <point p="(0,-4)" alignment="ne">y-intercept</point>
                    <point p="(-2,0)" alignment="nw">x-intercept</point>
                    <point p="(1,0)" alignment="ne">x-intercept</point>
                  </coordinates>
                  <annotations>
                    <annotation ref="figure"
                                text="The graph is a quartic function (with a W-shape) opening 
                                downwards with y-intercept at (0, -4), and x-intercepts at 
                                (-2, 0), and (1, 0).">
                      </annotation>
                  </annotations>
                </diagram>
              </prefigure>
            </image>
          </answer>
        </task>
    </exercise>
  </page>
</worksheet> 
